    &lt;CommentText&gt;Dear Mari,

Emergency Department - response
Thank you for your feedback on your recent visits to the Emergency Department (ED) of Queen Elizabeth Hospital. We take all the feedbacks seriously and I apologise that you felt that your experience was short of your expectation. I would like to reassure you that the department does its best to make sure all patients are seen and treated in a timely fashion. We aim to see, assess, treat, discharge or admit patients within 4 hours in-line with the national 4 hours target. We see and treat in accordance with the clinical priority and a referral to appropriate speciality if needed as was in your case. I would also like to reassure you that the ED staff have received the appropriate training in the insertion and removal of iv cannula. I am sorry to read that you felt â€˜fobbed off' when you requested for the cannula to be looked at. Please be assured I will be highlighting your experience to the whole ED team by sharing your experience with all staff so that we can learn from this. Once again thank you for taking the time to let us know of your experience as we appraise and learn from all feedback and I wish you the best of health going forward.

Surgery response
Hot food outside of meal times is accommodated if the kitchen is able to supply. If this is not possible a snack box is provided until next the next meal. I am sorry to read that you were given cold food. Please be assured that I have discussed your concerns raised with the surgical wards to learn from this.

If you would like your concerns investigated further and receive a formal response, please contact the Patient Advice &amp;amp; Liaison Service (PALS) team at the Queen Elizabeth Hospital on 020 8836 4592.

Glenda Moncar ED Matron
Louise Horan Matron- Surgery 

Queen Elizabeth Hospital Woolwich
Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Trust
